"1160":"1160","1180":"1180","1217":"1217","1216":"1216","1215":"1215","1127":"1127","1226":"1226","7 June 1167":"7 June 1167","1179":"1179","1167":"1167","1218":"1218","Somerset, England":"Somerset, England","Bishopstone, Montacute, Somerset, England":"Montacute, Somerset, England","Bishopstone, Sussex, England":"Bishopstone, Sussex, England","Shepton Montague, Somerset, England":"Shepton Montague, Somerset, England",", , Somerset, England, United Kingdom":"Somerset, England, United Kingdom","Montacute, Somerset, England":"Montacute, Somerset, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"of","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: possibly a metonymic occupational name for a fisherman, from <i>orfe</i>, a species of freshwater fish. Alternatively, a habitational name from Urff near Kassel, formerly Orpha."],"variants":[{"name":"Orff","meanings":["German: variant of   Orf  ."]}]},{"name":"Somerset","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English:","habitational name from the English county of Somerset, which takes its name from Somerton in Somerset (see   Summerton  ) + Old English <i>sǣte</i> ‘settlers, dwellers’. The <i>Somerset</i> family who are Dukes of Beaufort are descended from the Plantagenets. The surname was assumed by Charles <i>Somerset</i> (1460–1520), illegitimate son of Henry Beaufort, Duke of Somerset. The latter was himself descended illegitimately from Edward III through John of Gaunt. A later member of the family was Fitzroy <i>Somerset</i> (1788–1855), who, as Lord Raglan, was the commander of British forces in the Crimea, one of the men responsible for the charge of the Light Brigade.","possibly a habitational name from one or more places called with Old Norse <i>sumar</i> ‘summer’ + <i>sætr</i> ‘shieling, hill pasture’, such as Summerseat in Elton (Lancashire), but decisive northern early bearers are lacking."],"variants":[{"name":"Summerton","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of various places called Somerton, particularly in Oxfordshire and Somerset, but also in Lincolnshire and Norfolk, named with Old English <i>sumor</i> ‘summer’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’."]},{"name":"Summersett","meanings":["English (Yorkshire): variant of   Somerset  ."]}]},{"name":"Isabel","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."],"variants":[{"name":"Isabell","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]},{"name":"Isabelle","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , now in frequent use in the English-speaking world."]},{"name":"Isobella","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , which has been popular in England since the 18th century and has recently become the preferred form of the name."]},{"name":"Isobelle","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]},{"name":"Isobel","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Isabel ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":54,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Isabel of Somerset was born in 1161, in Bishopstone, Sussex, England, her father, Richard de Somerset, was 35 and her mother, Alice de Montague, was 41. She married William de Montague in 1179, in Shepton Montague, Somerset, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 2 daughters. She died in 1218, in Somerset, England, at the age of 57."},"et":{"1161–1218":"1161–1218","1160–1217":"1160–1217","1180–1226":"1180–1226","1183–1216":"1183–1216","1187–1217":"1187–1217","1127–Male":"1127–Surnud","1120–1167":"1120–1167","1187":"1187","before June 1217":"enne juunit 1217","1120":"1120","1161":"1161","1183":"1183","Aft 1217":"pärast 1217","1160":"1160","1180":"1180","1217":"1217","1216":"1216","1215":"1215","1127":"1127","1226":"1226","7 June 1167":"7. juuni 1167","1179":"1179","1167":"1167","1218"